`setState` is an asyncronous method, which means that the effect is not immediate. That is why you should pass the code you want to execute after as second parameter (callback) : `setState(updater[, callback])` ([source][1]).

```js
tokenAccess(){
    const hash = window.location.hash.substring(1);
    const hashArr = hash.split(/[=&amp;]/);
    console.log(hashArr);
    this.setState({
        access_token: hashArr[1],
        token_type: hashArr[3],
        expires_in: hashArr[5],
    }, () =&gt; {                   // This is the
        console.log(this.state); // callback as
    })                           // second parameter
}
```


  [1]: https://reactjs.org/docs/react-component.html#setstate

