All your attempts are hindered by the fact that `/app/appscripts/jenkins_modules` seems to contain all the elements on the same line, space separated. Default delimiter for mapfile is &quot;\n&quot;, so your array will only contain one element:

    $ mapfile -d&quot; &quot; -t mod &lt; &lt;(echo &quot;01_docker 02_gtw 99_mq_gtw&quot;);
    
    $ echo ${#mod[@]}
    3
    
    $ mapfile -t mod &lt; &lt;(echo &quot;01_docker 02_gtw 99_mq_gtw&quot;);
    
    $ echo ${#mod[@]}
    1

As you can see, without specifying the delimiter, the array has one element. 

You can use then C style loop to walk the array in reverse:

    $ mapfile -d&quot; &quot; -t mod &lt; &lt;(echo -n &quot;01_docker 02_gtw 99_mq_gtw&quot;);
    
    $ for ((i = ${#mod[@]}-1; i &gt;= 0 ; i--)); do echo &quot;$i - ${mod[$i]}&quot;; done
    2 - 99_mq_gtw
    1 - 02_gtw
    0 - 01_docker
    
    $ mapfile -t mod &lt; &lt;(echo &quot;01_docker 02_gtw 99_mq_gtw&quot;);
    
    $ for ((i = ${#mod[@]}-1; i &gt;= 0 ; i--)); do echo &quot;$i - ${mod[$i]}&quot;; done
    0 - 01_docker 02_gtw 99_mq_gtw

(as you can see without the delimiter set for mapfile it won&#39;t work)

Also, be careful about the new line at the end of the `/app/appscripts/jenkins_modules`, `-t` from mapfile won&#39;t remove it when the delimiter is set to &#39; &#39;

Your best bet would be to modify `/app/appscripts/jenkins_modules` to have one module per line.

